mitre_attack_techniques.signature_description: Adversaries may communicate using application layer protocols to avoid detection/network filtering by blending in with existing traffic.
Adversaries may employ a known encryption algorithm to conceal command and control traffic rather than relying on any inherent protections provided by a communication protocol.
Adversaries may inject code into processes in order to evade process-based defenses as well as possibly elevate privileges.
May try to detect the virtual machine to hinder analysis (VM artifact strings found in memory)
Uses HTTPS for network communication, use the SSL MITM Proxy cookbook for further analysis

text_highlighted: Would you like to check for new versions of Network Scanner automatically?

signature_matches.name: packed with Mpress
signature_matches.description: anti-analysis/packer/mpress
signature_matches.rule_src:
rule:
  meta:
    name: packed with Mpress
    namespace: anti-analysis/packer/mpress
    authors:
      - william.ballenthin@mandiant.com
    scopes:
      static: file
      dynamic: file
    att&ck:
      - Defense Evasion::Obfuscated Files or Information::Software Packing [T1027.002]
    mbc:
      - Anti-Static Analysis::Software Packing [F0001]
    references:
      - https://www.hexacorn.com/blog/2016/12/15/pe-section-names-re-visited/
  features:
    - or:
      - section: .MPRESS1
      - section: .MPRESS2
